Don't get me wrong, I do understand how annoying it must be to grow up with strict parents, but my childhood was a complete mess because of violence and a total lack of rules. I'd be out drinking on the sreets at the age of thirteen, nobody gave a damn about where I'd spend my nights. One time I got so drunk at 14 that my friends had to carry me home and just left me on my bed. I pissed myself, threw up and all - nobody noticed. I was so glad to have gotten away with that the next morning, now I know that I could have died that night. I've been dealing wi th alcohol abuse on and off since then, now I'm 23, got my degree and haven't had a single drop in 13 months. I love my parents and know they love me, but what they loved even more was their careers. They didn't only neglect me but also my younger siblings. When I was 14 my brothers were 3 and 5 ye ars old, they often got up at night to sleep in my parent's room or to get them to bring them back to bed and say goodnight one more time. My parents didn't like that and locked their door. Since I didn't have a key for my door, my brothers would both come into my bed to be close to somebody, and I had to share it with them which kept me from sleeping. I complained about it but nothing changed. When all of this started to show and my grades got worse and worse, my parents would pretend that it was all my fault. I could go on telling these stories for hours and it truly sickens me. Both ends of the spectrum can be very damaging.

I grew up with some of the most strict, selfish, meanest, abusive parents in the world.
My parents put me in the basement to sleep and if I wanted to do anything I had to give then two weeks notice. 
"Hey can I go to the mall" no. "Hey can I go to a friends house?" no. I think in the span of my 4 High school years living with them I went only a total of 10 outings with friends. 
Oh and I wasn't allowed to shower alone. I had to get my step mothers approval on how I looked ever morning before school. I've been late for school because she didn't like what I was wearing or how my hair was so I had to go back. I never bought my own clothing, that was also just on my bed when I would come home. Often clothing didn't fit (too small or short) but had to wear it anyway.
School, I loved school I never wanted to leave school. School mean't freedom. I had a long time BF they kept trying to get me to break up with him. (we're married now 17 yrs together)
After school I had and hour to walk 2 miles home. If I was even 10 min late. I was lectured and punished with earlier sleep time. I wasn't allowed to use to phone or watch tv. Had to clean the house every weekend often twice if even a little smudge was found. 
Often things were stolen from me. I was forced to get a job when I was 17 (not bad but I was unprepared for it) and because I wasn't 18 I had to put my money into my parents bank which I found out later they took $5000.00. For $1200 I bought a car when I was 18, learned to drive it and moved away.
So next time you think "omg my parents are so strict." think of all the freedoms you do have.

whenever people tell stories like this, i just don't understand why they put up with it? (honest question) when i was a teenager, there was literally nothing anyone could have done to make me follow arbitrary rules (rules that aren't the law - like: in germany you can't be out past midnight if you're under 18, so i followed the law by being home by midnight to not get my parents in trouble). knowing that, and trusting in me and my sense of responsibility, my parents basically let me do whatever i wanted (again: within legal boundaries, which we had discussed) but they made sure i knew i could always count on them if i got into trouble. did i have bad experiences because of my freedom? of course. did i still sometimes do things that weren't exactly legal? sure. do i sometimes regret the choices that i made (regarding hair-colour or clothing style or sexual partners)? you bet. but they were MY choices. and my parents were always there to help me deal with whatever had gone wrong. i think, overall, that made me a very responsible and mature person. and though i don't want children of my own, if i ever did wind up with a child, i'd raise it exactly the way i was raised. :3

commentThread.commentText:
Yep yep yep yep yep!!!! Imagine (being a girl + and an only child) x growing up in an Asian household = all these strict parents combined = my parents

Study even during summer, no dating/no boyfriend, home by sunset (elementary & highschool days), home by 9:00pm (university!), no sleepovers, no short shorts, no parties, no drinking, etc. And don't get me started on their expectations. They still believe that a diploma is the key to life, and that if my mom can get straight A's while studying full time and working at night, that I should be able to do the same.

Now almost 21, never partied, never been into clubs/bars, never had a sleepover.

On top of being strict, they're workaholics,  plus being an only child, equals me always alone. This resulted to me not being good at reading social cues,  can't keep life long friends, not functioning well or stresses out on things not being "perfect" or going the way I need it to, and lastly, I missed out a lot of experiences and opportunities on making mistakes and learning from them earlier on.
Don't get me wrong, I love my parents, I just wish they were more open.
Rant over...

It can go either way with the children of strict parents. I know my dad's friends daughter went wild. She got scolded if she didn't WRITE perfectly. She ended up saying fu and doing whatever though. I think the perfect way is to be in between. Being too lenient, or too strict can go pretty wrong for the kids in a multitude of ways. I know some kids where their worst case scenario was suicide. That is why I don't like super strict people, or people who shouldn't have had kids to begin with.

People in the comments are talking about their experience with their parents, but just wait until you become a parent yourself. You think your parents are strict on you now, but as you grow older you'll start to realize why they did what they did and really appreciate the depth of the meaning behind it. Why do you think Asians parents are mostly academic focused and strict towards their kids? It's so their kids can live a better life than they ever did. It's so they don't have to work in a restaurant or work in 100 degrees outside. That's why universities such as UC Berkeley and UCLA are nearly 50% Asians. Education is very important and it opens a lot of opportunities in our lives. On the side note, nobody else will sacrifice as much as our parents and tell us what to do other than our parents. The times we have with our parents now, cherish them. I'm speaking this as a 23 years old son, because people really don't cherish what they have until those things around them are gone forever. Our parents gave us everything and did their best. As they grow older, it's our turn to return the favor and protect them and look out for them. Be glad that we even have parents. Some people don't even have someone to nag to them. Please don't ever take life for granted.
